 <br>
That being said,I was sorta stunned at the lack of things a warrior can do in EQ compared to GS III,where I cut my teeth as a meleer.<br>
 <br>
Weapon choices mattered for more than raw DPS. Take good old shiny swords.<br>
 <br>
If I wanted a high crit rate but low damage otherwise,I'd take a rapier. I also had a much better chance of destroying my weapon. I could use a shield with that,which was handy for keeping my defense up. Fast weapon,which meant I could hit and button up for the return shot if need be.<br>
 <br>
If I wanted something more middle of the road,it was my broadsword, which I always favored. It wasn't a a critmonster, but hit respectably for damage and could do the job in any situation.<br>
 <br>
If I wanted brutal earthshaking utter one-shotting it'd be a claidmore. Slow,prone to giving the opponent plenty of time to hit a wide-open attacker if you didn't crit and stun...but massive damage and massive critical damage as well. A rapier can poke decently. Claidmores literally tore off limbs and crushed skulls by comparison.<br>
 <br>
Warriors in EQ have zip,zero,and nada special options based on their weapons choices. Given skills that ate stamina like hybrids eat mana to do special stuff (and tweak stamina recovery spells accordingly,like anyone cares) they'd have a LOT more in the way of options-and those skills could easily be weapon  and delay specific.<br>
 <br>
Start eating the stamina bar and take a speed hit to make all your weapon swings have a chance to 0-second interrupt stun with massive blows from a blunt weapon?<br>
<br>
Pull out that piercer, click on the technique hotbutton (C'mon purple bar...) and when it's finished cut loose with a single massive critical strike (and again,stamina drain...)<br>
 <br>
Wield that twohander in great sweeping arcs to PBAE every mob in the crowd? Tiring (there goes that stamina bar again) but you just managed to rampage the crowd for a second or two...till you tired out and &quot;stunned&quot; from exhaustion!<br>
 <br>
Give the techniques a recovery time and stamina cost and you've got plenty to work with without breaking the class. Warriors should be different the way knights and pallies are.<br>
